'''Chicken Bone Beach''' was a [[Racial segregation in the United States|racially segregated]] section of the [[Atlantic Ocean]] beach at [[Atlantic City, New Jersey]] (between Missouri and Mississippi Avenues<ref>{{cite book|last=Stansfield|first=Charles A.|title=Vacationing on the Jersey Shore: Guide to the Beach Resorts: Past and Present|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BKDxOngkTqkC&pg=PA88|year=2004|publisher=Stackpole|isbn=9780811729703|page=88}}</ref>) known for attracting many [[African American]] entertainers. It was given this name by the locals due to the volume of chicken bones found in this segregated area during regular clean ups.<ref name=history>{{cite web|url=http://www.chickenbonebeach.org/black-history/|website=ChickenBoneBeach.org|accessdate=21 Feb 2016|title=Our History: Black History|last=Hopper|first=Dale}}</ref>
==Background== Blacks and whites lived in the area side by side with few problems after the [[American Civil War]]. It wasn't until 1900 that the beach became segregated, due in part to pressures by local businesses. It remained a ''blacks only'' beach until the passing of the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]].<ref name="blackpast">{{cite web|url=http://www.blackpast.org/aah/chicken-bone-beach-atlantic-city-new-jersey-1900| title=Chicken Bone Beach, Atlantic City, New Jersey (1900- )|website=BlackPast.org|last=Stephens|first=Ronald J.|accessdate=21 Feb 2016}}</ref>
While there were no signs nor laws prohibiting blacks from enjoying the entirety of the beach, the segregation was rigidly enforced by local authorities or more commonly, white beachgoers.<ref name="history" /> The Atlantic City Beach Patrol was officially desegregated, but its black members were in practice consigned to Chicken Bone Beach.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Cunningham|first1=John T.|last2=Cole|first2=Kenneth D.|title=Atlantic City|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4NQm2sacUfwC&pg=PA50|year=2000|publisher=Arcadia|isbn=9780738504261|page=50}}</ref>
